06320nam a22009135i 9780226643281DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018054724  a97802266432817 a10.7208/97802266432812doi  a(DE-B1597)535736  a(OCoLC)1105199829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHT334.M3bG37 2019 4aHT334.M3bG37 2020 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a307.76409599162231 aGarrido, Marco Z., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Patchwork City :bClass, Space, and Politics in Metro Manila /cMarco Z. Garrido. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b21 halftones, 3 line drawings, 16 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Stakes and Approach -- t2. The Argument -- tPART ONE. From Urban Fragmentation to Class Division -- t3. Interspersion -- t4. Imposing Boundaries: Villagers -- t5. Boundary Imposition: Squatters -- tPART TWO. From Class Division to Political Dissensus -- tIntroduction to Part Two -- t6. The Politics of Electoral Siege -- t7. The Politics of Recognition -- t8. Dissensus -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Selecting Cases and Getting Access -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn contemporary Manila, slums and squatter settlements are peppered throughout the city, often pushing right up against the walled enclaves of the privileged, creating the complex geopolitical pattern of Marco Z. Garrido’s “patchwork city.” Garrido documents the fragmentation of Manila into a mélange of spaces defined by class, particularly slums and upper- and middle-class enclaves. He then looks beyond urban fragmentation to delineate its effects on class relations and politics, arguing that the proliferation of these slums and enclaves and their subsequent proximity have intensified class relations. For enclave residents, the proximity of slums is a source of insecurity, compelling them to impose spatial boundaries on slum residents. For slum residents, the regular imposition of these boundaries creates a pervasive sense of discrimination. Class boundaries then sharpen along the housing divide, and the urban poor and middle class emerge not as labor and capital but as squatters and “villagers,” Manila’s name for subdivision residents. Garrido further examines the politicization of this divide with the case of the populist president Joseph Estrada, finding the two sides drawn into contention over not just the right to the city, but the nature of democracy itself. The Patchwork City illuminates how segregation, class relations, and democracy are all intensely connected. It makes clear, ultimately, that class as a social structure is as indispensable to the study of Manila—and of many other cities of the Global South—as race is to the study of American cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEqualityzPhilippineszManila Metropolitan Area. 0aEqualityzPhilippineszManila. 0aManila Metropolitan Area (Philippines)xPolitics and government 0aManila Metropolitan Area (Philippines)xPolitics and government. 0aMetropolitan areasxSocial aspectszPhilippines. 0aMiddle classxPolitical activityzPhilippineszManila Metropolitan Area. 0aMiddle classxPolitical activityzPhilippineszManila. 0aMiddle classzPhilippineszManila Metropolitan Area. 0aMiddle classzPhilippineszManila. 0aSocial classeszPhilippineszManila Metropolitan Area. 0aSocial classeszPhilippineszManila. 0aSocial conflictzPhilippineszManila Metropolitan Area. 0aSocial conflictzPhilippineszManila. 0aUrban poorxPolitical activity